snippet.textDisplay:
Samsung has done some pretty good stuff with numbers..... but quite frankly I didn’t see as much of a leap in quality over pro max as has been shown across platforms.
In this video i was surprised to see that iphone’s captures were actually better in almost all scenarios except the zoom past 10x (would rarely use unless one is spying) , front camera sharpness & 8K video of samsung (unusable by general consumers since its not practical to use in daily shots),,,,
rest of the shots iphone was producing way better looking captures..... AND THATS EXCATLY WHAT A REGULAR CONSUMER USES !!
Practically analysing this video, i think iPhones still does way better as a daily driver because we wont use 100x zoon daily, we wont record videos at 8k (daily basis-regular shots)..... rest for all things iphone output was better by far.....
And dont get me wrong.... i have a pro max as well as a note 10+ so am not biased..... and i have been thinking of picking this ultra as well but i think now that i shall stick to my note 10+.....
As it is androids bump up every spec but produce very inconsistent results..... shall stick to iphone as daily driver !!
Thanks for sharing this video.... u have saved me a lot of money !!

snippet.textDisplay: I don't know if it's a software issue, hardware limitation or even a faulty unit, but the video quality of the Samsung is not up to what the company is bragging about. There's a lot of focus hunting, noise, frame rate dips (in low light), micro stuttering... And the 8k is not even usable. There are some weird decisions like when you're going through the zooming ranges, sometimes a lower "zoom" (like 2 times) produces a worse image then on a greater (optical) one. The 100x is a joke, 30x isn't up to the quality you would expect from such an expensive device. Samsung really dropped the ball on this unit. I'm a note 10 owner, for the record.
snippet.textOriginal: I don't know if it's a software issue, hardware limitation or even a faulty unit, but the video quality of the Samsung is not up to what the company is bragging about. There's a lot of focus hunting, noise, frame rate dips (in low light), micro stuttering... And the 8k is not even usable. There are some weird decisions like when you're going through the zooming ranges, sometimes a lower "zoom" (like 2 times) produces a worse image then on a greater (optical) one.
